As for why I'm telling you this, is simple. I didn't really plan for much sexual stuff until the last 5 days of Christmas, which I'm now writing. Since the characters are, or are about to be, engaged, which at the time permitted limited sexual contact, and both oral and anal sex were seen as "mediums for betrothed couples to remain in good standing" as, though this was more common in Northern Europe, France, Italy, and Greece, not Spain, England, or Poland.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x9fBEOC3ujw

One thing that seems obvious to me from historical accounts is the fact that historical societies had their own unwritten rules, and of course there was much less public surveillance. One big scandal in my country during Medieval times was that a city's gay population would meet at night in the city park, which was a park because part of the city's giant church had collapsed and no-one bothered to clear the ruins. So not only were the gays literally fucking in the house of God, but many of the ones captured were influential people. The perspective here being that committing the serious crime of faggotry was still relatively safe to do, en masse, by simply stepping out of sight in the middle of the city. There's also stuff like the trials of God that were common in Medieval justice. Stuff like walking X paces while holding a piece of red hot metal. If you could do it uninjured, clearly God favored you and you were innocent. Or if you were innocent, but the wound healed quickly, clearly God favored you and you were innocent. Sounds impossible, but these had something like a 50% rate of God favoring you. Because the entire thing was in the hands of priests, who would speak at length with the accused, and essentially acted like a hidden judiciary. So if they weren't keen on putting someone on the block, they'd do something like filibuster until the metal had cooled down enough to hold. They were also the ones in charge of inspecting the wounds (because God), so they could just dead-ass say "yeah, God totally healed this man, let him go".

A lot of modern perception of Medieval history comes down to people just taking everything at face value, with a nice dash of Renaissance snobbery. Which is wild, considering some of the incredibly detailed period reports that are sitting in archives across Europe. At least understanding has grown. The stuff people in the 80's and 90's thought about history almost seems farcical.

Anonymous Sat 24 Dec 2022 01:03:13 No.53227529 Report

>>53226834
In all seriousness, it was this horrible grimderp thing I came up with when I was depressed a few years back. It had to do with time travel, parallel worlds, and beings whose ancestors were human, who had technology vastly more advanced than our own, whom it wouldn't be entirely inaccurate to call Gods. It started with a reading a really odd, even by fanfic standards, super duper megacrossover thing that mashed up Ranma 1/2, Ah My Goddess, H. P. Lovecraft, Evangelion, and I don't even know what else, with a smug asshole author avatar telling the main characters from the other franchises why they all sucked while he saved the world. I wanted to start with a similar premise, but one that examined this one's unexamined assumptions. The main protagonist was an American who married in Japan, because lol weeb, whose wife and kids died in the Tokyo bombing of 1994, who joined the Army in search of either revenge or an opportunity to die fighting. He survived horrific fighting in Korea--imagine everything you read about the Korean War, but add competent commanders on the North Korean side, with mechanized armies, tactical nukes, and big stockpiles of poison gas and tailored biologicals. Things get worse and worse, but he keeps surviving. The Gods notice him and promise him a chance at one last good fight, one where he can make a difference. He accepts and gets thrown into a much larger war for all existing--and the Gods who took him on are losing to beings who want to destroy everything everywhere and start over. It is a war across all space and time, across thousands of parallel universes and alternate histories. And his side is losing. But the Gods keep snatching him and a few other survivors out at the very last moment and throwing them back into the line, to try to make a difference at critical junctures of history, here and there, so that something can be salvaged, so that a remnant of a remnant can survive. It's all horribly depressing.
